            section.section
                .container-small
                    .row
                        .col-12
                            p.text Exit Tiger Woods and Phil Mickelson. Enter Chanelle Wangari, an eight year old Kenyan golfer who wants to give Woods a run for his money.

                            p.text Wangari is a class three student at Makini School.
                                br
                                | By the way, she turns nine in September but before then she wants to have won the the US Kids Golf World Championship that will be held in Pinehurst, North Carolina from July 30th to August 1, 2015.


            section.section-step.section-step--eight
                .container-fluid
                    .row
                        .col-12
                            h2.section-title Here are 8 amazing facts about Wangari…


                .container-small
                    .row
                        .col-12
                            h3.fact-title
                                span.fact-title__num 8
                                span.fact-title__num-txt Eight
                                | Wangari does all the things eight year old’s do

                            p.text She goes to class during the week and has homework which she endeavors to finish by Friday afternoon so she can play golf.

                            p.text
                                span.text__quote “It is a lot of running, we have to make it to practice a bunch of times in a week.
                                    br
                                    | There are a lot of early mornings and cramped schedules, especially ahead of a big tournament, but Chanelle loves golf, which makes it all worth it,”
                                    br
                                    | says Maureen Wangari, Chanelle’s mother.

                            p.text Wangari says she enjoys school very much.

                            p.text
                                p.text__quote “I love math, numbers are really fun. They help me with golf, you can see how you’re doing in the game, just by using math problems.”


            section.section-step.section-step--seven
                .container-small
                    .row
                        .col-12
                            h3.fact-title
                                span.fact-title__num 7
                                span.fact-title__num-txt Seven
                                | Long attention span – but for golf

                            p.text When Wangari is on the golf course, the game is the only thing on her mind. Yes! No getting distracted. When she plays at the US Kids Golf World Championship, it will be her first time to travel to the US.

                            p.text
                                span.text__quote This is what Wangari said when I asked her what she wanted to know about North Carolina. “How is the humidity? It will affect the distance I can hit the ball. I really can’t wait to go to Disney World, right after the competition we are going there and I am so excited!”


            section.section-step.section-step--six
                .container-small
                    .row
                        .col-12
                            h3.fact-title
                                span.fact-title__num 6
                                span.fact-title__num-txt Six
                                | Travels because of golf

                            p.text To qualify for the US Kids Golf World Championship, Wangari had to be top three in the Africa Junior Golf Championship that was held in South Africa in September 2014. She has played in Malaysia and will travel to Italy in October of 2015 to play.

                            p.text
                                span.text__quote “I’m very excited to go to Europe to golf. I haven’t been there before and I want to play on their courses, I hear they’re really beautiful,” she says.


